<!--This article is written in British English with Oxford Spelling. Please keep
this in mind when editing this page.--> {{Infobox disease| Name = Floater |
Image = Floaters.png | Caption = Simulated image of floaters against a blue sky
| DiseasesDB = 31270 | ICD10 = | ICD9 = | ICDO = | OMIM = | MedlinePlus = 002085
| eMedicineSubj = | eMedicineTopic = | MeshID = | }} 'Floaters' are deposits of
various size, shape, consistency, refractive index, and motility within the
eye’s vitreous humour, which is normally transparent.<ref name="Cline">Cline D;
Hofstetter HW; Griffin JR. Dictionary of Visual Science. 4th ed. Butterworth-
Heinemann, Boston 1997. ISBN 0-7506-9895-0</ref><ref name=facts>{{cite web
  | title = Facts about floaters publisher = National Eye Institute month =
  | December | year = 2007 url =
  | http://www.nei.nih.gov/health/floaters/index.asp accessdate =February
  | 2008}}</ref> At a young age, the vitreous is
transparent, but as one ages, imperfections gradually develop. The common type
of floater, which is present in most people’s eyes, is due to degenerative
changes of the vitreous humour. The perception of floaters is known as
myodesopsia,<ref>From Greek [http://www.zeno.org/Pape-1880/A/μυιώδης μυιώδης]
"fly-like" (Myiodes was also the name of a fly-deterring deity) and ὄψις
"sight."</ref> or less commonly as myodaeopsia, myiodeopsia, myiodesopsia.<ref
name="Cline"/> They are also called Muscae volitantes (Latin: "flying flies"),
or mouches volantes (from the French). Floaters are visible because of the
shadows they cast on the retina<ref name=pamphlet>American Academy of
Ophthalmology. "Floaters and Flashes: A Closer Look" (pamphlet) San Francisco:
AAO, 2006. ISBN 1-56055-371-5</ref> or refraction of the light that passes
through them, and can appear alone or together with several others in one’s
visual field. They may appear as spots, threads, or fragments of cobwebs, which
float slowly before the observer’s eyes.<ref name=facts/> Since these objects
exist within the eye itself, they are not optical illusions but are entoptic
phenomena.
